<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-385-188  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 385 188.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  April 30 1990 v139 pA1(N) pA1(L) 40 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan sets sights on winning lead in new computers; fielddominated by U.S.; goal is software that allows thousands ofprocessors to operate in tandem. (parallel processing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sanger, David E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Japanese Government plans an effort to master the technologyknown as 'massive parallel processing,' which uses combinations ofthousands of processors to solve complicated problems such asrecognizing images; translating spoken languages; and trackingthings that come in multitudes, from gene pools to incomingmissiles.andP;  Japanese plans in this area are included in theJapanese Government's first assessment of how it should follow upon its 'Fifth Generation' project, which aimed at the creation ofcomputers that reason.andP;  The Fifth Generation project, which hasexisted for nine years, was purposed to establish the fundamentalsof 'intelligent' machines, but a shift to parallel processingseems to indicate that early goals were too ambitious.andP;  Japan'snew effort will focus on hardware that is relatively simple, butsoftware that runs such systems will be enormously complex.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanJapanese CompetitionParallel ProcessingFifth GenerationComputer industryArtificial intelligenceGovernment Funding.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>